## Phase 3: Content Generation

Once outlines are approved, generate workshop content ONE LESSON AT A TIME:

### Content Generation Workflow (Per Lesson):

#### Step 1: Read and Understand

1. **Read the OUTLINE.adoc file** for the current lesson
   ```
   Read: asciidoc/courses/workshop-[slug]/modules/[X]/lessons/[Y]/OUTLINE.adoc
   ```
   - Note source courses
   - Note specific adaptations required
   - Note which rules apply
   - Note image requirements

2. **Read the source lesson(s)** from the specified course(s)
   ```
   Read: asciidoc/courses/[source-course]/modules/[module]/lessons/[lesson]/lesson.adoc
   ```
   - Understand the full content
   - Identify sections to include/exclude
   - Note examples to adapt

3. **Read previous workshop lesson** (if not the first lesson)
   ```
   Read: asciidoc/courses/workshop-[slug]/modules/[X]/lessons/[Y-1]/lesson.adoc
   ```
   - Understand what was just taught
   - Ensure proper scaffolding and context

#### Step 2: Generate Content

4. **Adapt and generate the full lesson content** following:

   **From .cursor/rules/asciidoc-syntax.mdc:**
   - ‚ö†Ô∏è **NO MARKDOWN** - only AsciiDoc format
   - TWO line breaks between all elements (headers, paragraphs, lists)
   - Proper list spacing (blank line before lists)

   **From .cursor/review-lesson-content.mdc:**
   - Two-part opening pattern:
     - Part 1: Context from previous lesson OR why topic matters
     - Part 2: "In this lesson, you will learn..."
   - Action-oriented headers in sentence case (not questions)
   - "you will" tone (never "we will" or "you'll")
   - Length under 5 minutes, 1-2 concepts max
   - Casual, friendly, no jargon

   **From .cursor/rules/slides-formatting.mdc (if instructor-led):**
   - `[.slide.discrete]` for opening section
   - `[.slide]` for main sections
   - `[.slide.discrete]` for subsections
   - `[.summary]` for summary section
   - `[.col-2]` layouts for images

   **From .cursor/write-lesson-summary.mdc:**
   - Bullet points with **bold** concept names
   - Brief descriptions after each concept
   - Forward reference to next lesson

   **From .cursor/technical-lesson-review.mdc:**
   - Opening must have level-2 header after attributes
   - Admonitions must have titles
   - Proper AsciiDoc code blocks ([source,cypher] with ----)

   **From .cursor/rules/neo4j-cypher.mdc (if Cypher present):**
   - Use COUNT {} subqueries instead of OPTIONAL MATCH for counts
   - Use pattern comprehensions for nested values

   **For Data Modeling Lessons (CRITICAL):**
   - **Focus on "WHY" not "what"** - Explain reasoning, not just definitions
   - **Compare with relational** - Show why graph approach is better, especially for many-to-many relationships
   - **Explain each decision** - When you say "Customer is a node," explain WHY (has independent existence, own data)
   - **For many-to-many relationships** - Always compare pivot tables vs. graph relationships with examples:
     ```
     Relational: orders JOIN order_details JOIN products (3 tables, 2 JOINs)
     Graph: (Order)-[:ORDERS]->(Product) (direct traversal, no JOINs)
     ```
